<br>
Vittore Cipriani was an Italian immigrant to London, who came with his father's theatre company.  The company did well enough that Vittore's father was able to play off the upper class's love of opera and eventually buy his own building, which was converted to a theatre/opera house.  After his father's death due to illness, Vittore combined his keen wit, love for the show, and ability to talk people into thinking his ideas were their own to make the small opera house a success.<br>
<br>
Teatro del Capricini became the widely known 'secret little place' for a good show amongst the upper crust, and Vittore had just made enough lucre to purchase geneology papers proving that the Capricini's were decended from Italian nobility.  Just mere steps from fame and fortune, Vittore's good luck hit a brick wall.<br>
<br>
One of those bitter bastard Nosferatu, jealous that someone of Vittore's average looks and fat Italian opera guy physique could become such a darling socialite, embraced him and abandoned him.  Unable to let go of his life's work in unlife, Vittore made ghouls of several assistants, had them provide excuses of being 'in seclution' due to a 'horrible family illness' and began to run the Teatro in secret from its deep basements.<br>
<br>
The success of the Teatro del Capricini continued, and Vittore has made contact with London's Nosferatu warren.  The warren appreciates Vittore's ability to eavesdrop on the well-to-do, and find great humor in the number of Toreador that must 'make nice' with him in order to attend his popular shows.<br>
<br>
